[𝘞𝘰𝘳𝘬𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘪𝘯 𝘱𝘶𝘣𝘭𝘪𝘤 𝘶𝘴𝘦𝘥 𝘵𝘰 𝘧𝘦𝘦𝘭 𝘨𝘦𝘯𝘦𝘳𝘰𝘶𝘴. 𝘕𝘰𝘸 𝘪𝘵 𝘧𝘦𝘦𝘭𝘴 𝘤𝘰𝘮𝘱𝘭𝘪𝘤𝘢𝘵𝘦𝘥.

So many marketers are turning processes and skills and knowledge into little portable objects that can be saved, exported, reused and 𝘀𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗲𝗱 𝗼𝗻 𝘀𝗼𝗰𝗶𝗮𝗹. As Katie Parrott said in Superpath recently: "Skills are the new thought leadership."

This is cool because those artifacts are reusable to you, which helps you work faster. But if you share these things on social as so many people do, it’s also reusable by other people. And while there’s some value in that, there is risk too.

I have a few Claude Skills that I use frequently. I find the process of making them to be fun at times, and depressing at others. I really enjoy stepping back from my day to work, analyzing the task and trying to streamline it. I think there’s a lot of value in doing this for almost every task we do from time to time. That’s the fun part. The part I dislike is feeling like productizing my work to that degree makes it feel like a commodity. 

I mean, I'm worth more than the sum of my .md files, right? RIGHT?!?!

Am I overreacting? Probably. But am I sharing my artifacts on social? Not right now.

What do you think?

